1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 g6 8. Rc1 (
8. cxd5 {is a bit hasty:} exd5 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. b4 O-O 11. O-O Be6 {[%csl Ge6]
Black had no problems developing the bishop, and} 12. b5 {can be met by} c5 $1
$132 {, with adequate counterplay for Black.}) ({But} 8. Qc2 {is also playable.
}) 8... Nd7 {[%csl Gc8] Although it is not a huge problem, Black will have to
find a way to develop the Bc8 now.} ({Of course not} 8... Bg7 $4 9. cxd5 exd5
10. Nxd5 $18) 9. Be2 {Thinking about White's plans, the bishop seems better
placed on e2. The d3-square is often useful to manoeuvre a knight to c5.} ({
Also, in the line} 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 a6 12. a4 Qd6 $1 13. b5 (13.
Qb3 {is more precise.}) 13... axb5 14. axb5 {, Black has the active response}
c5 $1 $132 {[%csl Gd3] , which wouldn't be possible with the bishop on e2.})
9... Bg7 10. cxd5 {White has waited until Black had developed the knight to d7
and the bishop to g7 to go for this exchange in the centre. This seems the
best way to pose some practical problems for Black.} exd5 11. b4 ({White can
play} 11. O-O {first, but in this case, Black has the extra option of} Qd6 $5 {
[%csl Gb4] , as the queen belongs to d6 in this structure, and it makes
White's plan of advancing on the queenside harder.} ({Although} 11... O-O {
is also possible, after which} 12. b4 a6 13. a4 Qd6 {leads to typical
positions.})) 11... a6 $1 ({The text is more precise than} 11... Qd6 {, when
White plays} 12. b5 {, and Black can't reply c6-c5, as the Nc3 is defended.}
O-O 13. O-O Nb6 14. bxc6 bxc6 15. Na4 $14 {[%csl Ga7,Gc6] This is the kind of
structure that should be avoided by Black. The presence of the a7-pawn
deprives the rook of active play along the a-file and provides one more target
for White. Many model games show how White can work this advantage, but the
most instructive which comes to my mind is Smyslov-Keres, 1948.}) 12. a4 Qd6 $5
{A new move by Giri, which solves Black's opening problems very well. The
queen often goes to d6 to control some squares on the queenside, defend c6 and
allow Black to mobilize forces in the best way (Nf6/b6-Be6).} ({Previous games
saw} 12... O-O 13. b5 axb5 14. axb5 Qd6 $1 15. O-O {, but Black should be able
to equalize here as well with correct play:} Nb6 16. Qb3 ({Black has no
problems in case of} 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. Rb1 Rb8 18. Na4 Nxa4 19. Qxa4 Bf5 20.
Rxb8 Rxb8 21. Rc1 Bd7 $11 {Vorontsov,P (2548)-Quesada Perez,Y (2642)/Pan
American Intercollegiate-chT 2018 (6.1)/1/2-1/2 This is the difference: If
White only attacks c6, Black has no problems defending it. On the other hand,
it is not easy to find a way of increasing the pressure for White.}) 16... Rb8
17. Nd1 $5 {[%cal Gd1b2,Gb2d3,Gd3c5] White goes for the typical idea of
manoeuvring the knight to c5 while keeping the tension on the queenside.} Bf5 (
{Black also looks very solid after} 17... Be6 18. Nb2 Rfc8 19. Nd3 Nd7 $11) 18.
Nb2 Rfc8 19. Nd3 {Now Black decided to take the concrete approach} Bxd3 $5 20.
Qxd3 c5 21. dxc5 Rxc5 $11 {Carlsen,M (2876)-Topalov,V (2798)/ Norway Chess 3rd
2015 (1) /0-1, with a balanced game. The isolated pawn is not a serious
problem here as it is well defended, and Black can develop his own active play
on the dark squares.}) 13. b5 ({Nothing is changed by} 13. Qb3 O-O 14. b5 axb5
15. axb5 Nf6 16. O-O Be6 17. Na4 Nd7 {, and we've transposed to the game.})
13... axb5 (13... cxb5 $5 14. axb5 a5 $5 {[%csl Ga5,Yd5] is the way if Black
looks for some imbalance.}) 14. axb5 Nb6 $1 15. O-O (15. Qb3 {now can be
answered by} c5 $1 {This breakthrough is possible because of Black's last move.
} 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. O-O Qd6 18. Rfd1 Ra3 19. Qb2 O-O $11 {and Black is fine.})
15... Be6 $1 16. Qb3 Nd7 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Ge6] This is the point of Giri's idea:
At the cost of delaying 0-0 for a few moves, Black has achieved the ideal
set-up for his pieces, avoiding any problems of development. By achieving
harmonious coordination, Black also makes sure that he won't face problems
keeping the c6-pawn defended.} 17. Na4 (17. e4 $5 {would be the only way to
exploit Black's move order, but now it is time for} O-O $1 ({But not} 17...
dxe4 18. Nxe4 Qf4 19. Bc4 $1 $36 {, when White has some initiative.}) 18. bxc6
bxc6 19. exd5 cxd5 $11 {, and Black is ok.}) 17... O-O 18. Nc5 Nxc5 19. Rxc5
Bd7 20. Rfc1 Ra7 $1 {As c6 is well defended and White has not been able to
increase the pressure by now, Black has time to prepare counterplay on the
a-file.} 21. Ne1 {Bringing the knight to the queenside seems the only
constructive plan for White.} Rfa8 22. bxc6 bxc6 23. Nd3 Ra1 $1 {Just in time!
The exchange of one pair of rooks reduces the pressure on c6.} 24. Qd1 Rxc1 25.
Rxc1 h5 26. Ra1 (26. Qc2 Bf6 27. Nc5 Be8 $11 {is also harmless for Black.})
26... Rxa1 27. Qxa1 Qb8 28. Nc5 Be8 29. g3 Bf8 30. Qc1 Bd6 31. Kg2 1/2-1/2

