{White has the simple plan of Nd2-b3 and a4-a5, with prospects of pressure on
the queenside. Find the best way of developing Black's pieces.} 16... Nf8 $1 {
[%cal Gf8e6] The knight will be well placed on e6.} ({Much better than} 16...
Nf6 17. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5] , when the knight struggles to find a useful
role on f6 and the c5-square is unprotected.}) 17. Nd2 Ra7 $1 {At the same
time anticipating Nb3 and overprotecting b7.} 18. Nb3 Ne6 19. Rfe1 Bf8 $1 {
Now it is time to place the bishop on a better diagonal.} 20. a5 Qd8 $1 $15 {
[%cal Gf8d6,Gf8b4,Gd8g5,Gd8h4,Ye6g5] ;Kamsky,G (2723)-Aronian,L (2737)/Sochi
FIDE GP 2008 (4)/1/2-1/2 Black has secured all important points on the
queenside and found a nice set-up. His position might look a bit cramped, but
it is actually full of potential, with ideas on both flanks like Bb4, Qh4-Ng5,
etc.} *

[Event "Tata Steel-A 73rd"]
[Site "Wijk aan Zee"]
[Date "2011.01.29"]
[Round "12"]
[White "Anand, Viswanathan"]
[Black "Giri, Anish"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "D43"]
[WhiteElo "2810"]
[BlackElo "2686"]
[Annotator "IM Renato Quintiliano"]
[PlyCount "99"]
[EventDate "2011.01.14"]
[EventRounds "13"]
[EventCountry "NED"]
[EventCategory "20"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 g6 8. Bd3
Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Rc1 (10. e4 {is the mainline.}) 10... dxc4 ({I usually
prefer to wait until White plays e3-e4 to take on c4:} 10... Nd7 11. e4 dxc4
12. Bxc4) 11. Bxc4 Nd7 12. e4 {Anand advances the pawn anyway.} ({My advice of
waiting until e3-e4 to release the tension in the centre comes from a personal
experience in this line:} 12. Bb3 $5 {, keeping flexibility.} Rd8 (12... e5 $2
{is bad due to} 13. Ne4 $1 Qe7 14. d5 $1 $16 {, and White develops a strong
initiative, using the light squares in the centre.}) 13. Qc2 Qe7 (13... e5 $2
14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Qxg6 $18 {Another important detail of keeping
the pawn on e3.}) 14. Ne2 $5 {An interesting idea, preventing Black from
developing the bishop to b7 and maybe aiming for Nf4-d3 to fight against both
e6-e5 and c6-c5.} ({Later, studying this game I found out that Anand had faced
this same position as Black in the past, but after the natural but soft} 14.
Rfd1 $6 {Black had no problems finishing his development.} b6 15. a3 Bb7 16.
Ba2 a6 {[%cal Yc6c5] ;Salov,V (2680)-Anand,V (2770)/Hoogovens Wijk aan Zee
1998 (3)/0-1, and Black is ready to play c6-c5 soon. For example:} 17. e4 $2 c5
18. d5 b5 $1 $17 {[%cal Yc5c4,Gd7e5] , and we have a typical case in which
White's centre becomes a source of problems, as it can't be properly supported.
}) 14... Kh7 $2 {I was still dreaming of e6-e5.} ({Instead, I should've played
} 14... Nb6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7e8] , followed by Bd7-e8, which is a typical way
for Black to finish development in such positions, with a slightly cramped but
solid and totally playable position.}) 15. h4 $1 e5 16. Ng3 Re8 17. h5 $16 {
Flores,D (2567)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2483)/American Continental 13th 2017 (6)/
1/2-1/2 , and White achieved a clear advantage, although in the end I managed
to save the game by some miracle.}) 12... c5 $5 $146 {This was a new idea by
Giri at the time.} (12... e5 {is more common, leading to Position 3.}) ({
I think Anand was hardly surprised by this move, as he used a similar idea
himself 5 years before this game:} 12... Qe7 13. Re1 Rd8 14. Qe2 c5 $1 15. d5
Nb6 16. Bb3 exd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Be6 $11 {, and after equalizing
without problems, Black squeezed the endgame into a win.}) 13. d5 ({In a
recent blitz game, White play was too careless:} 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. b4 $2 Nd7
15. Qe2 Qe7 16. b5 {Lautier,J (2658)-Gelfand,B (2676)/Razuvaev Memorial online
blitz 2020 (6)/1/2-1/2 , and here, with the simple continuation} b6 17. Rfd1
Bb7 18. Nd4 Rac8 $19 {[%cal Rg7a1,Rb7h1] , Black could have achieved an almost
winning position, in view of his powerful bishops and White's exposed
queenside.}) (13. e5 Qe7 {would lead to Position 4-5.}) 13... Nb6 14. b3 (14.
Bb3 $2 {is a mistake in view of} c4 $1 15. Bc2 exd5 16. exd5 Bg4 $17 {[%csl
Rd5] , and White soon faces problems with the pawn on d5.}) 14... exd5 15. Nxd5
Qd8 16. h3 {Anand prevents Bg4, but I'm not sure if this was Giri's intention,
as the bishop is better placed on e6, fighting for the d5 square.} (16. Qe2 {
perhaps would be better, aiming to improve White's control over d5, when the
game could continue} Nxc4 17. bxc4 Re8 18. Rfd1 Bf5 $5 19. Ne3 Bd7 $11 {
, with a dynamically balanced position.}) 16... Nxc4 17. bxc4 Re8 18. Re1 Bd7
19. Qd2 Rc8 20. Qf4 b5 $5 {A very energetic move, aiming to open lines for the
bishops and get a passed pawn on the c-file.} 21. e5 g5 $1 ({After} 21... bxc4
{, White could try} 22. Nf6+ $5 Bxf6 23. exf6 {, and Black shouldn't
underestimate his risks on the kingside, for instance:} Rc6 $2 24. Red1 $1 Rxf6
25. Qxh6 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Rf5 26. Rxc4 {[%cal Yc4h4]} Rh5 27. Qd2 $16 {, and
White keeps strong pressure.}) 22. Qg3 {Anand is still thinking about ideas on
the kingside.} (22. Qe3 $5 {or}) (22. Qe4 $5 {was also possible, keeping the
queen centralized.}) 22... bxc4 23. Red1 (23. Rcd1 $5 {looks more logical, but
after the same reply} Rc6 {, White had to find} 24. Nd2 $1 {, which is not
obvious at all, as Anand clearly wanted to keep his pieces close to the
kingside.} ({I assume that he rejected} 24. Ne3 {due to} c3 $1 $132) 24... c3
$1 25. Nxc3 c4 26. Nf3 Rg6 $5 27. Ne4 $36 {, and White keeps some initiative.})
23... Rc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Yc6e6,Yc6g6] A very nice idea, as the rook is
very useful on the third rank to either increase pressure on e5 or to be
transferred to the kingside. Giri's dynamic play is a nice example of how to
undermine White's stability in the centre.} 24. Ne3 ({An equal ending would
arise in case of} 24. Rxc4 Qb8 $1 25. Nf6+ $1 Bxf6 26. Rxd7 Bxe5 27. Nxe5 Qxe5
28. Qxe5 Rxe5 29. Rxa7 $11) 24... Qc7 25. Nxc4 (25. h4 gxh4 $5 26. Qxh4 Rg6 $13
{looks double-edged.}) (25. Nd5 $5 Qb7 26. Ne3 Qc7 27. Nd5 $11) 25... Be6 26.
h4 $6 {This seems like a dubious idea, as White isn't able to open the
kingside.} (26. Nd6 Rd8 {[%cal Rg7e5] doesn't accomplishes anything, either.})
({But} 26. Rd6 $5 {was possible, although it doesn't pose problems for Black:}
Bxc4 27. Rxc4 Bxe5 (27... Rxd6 28. exd6 Qc6 29. h4 $5 $13 {looks more
complicated now.}) 28. Rxc6 Bxg3 29. Rxc7 Bxc7 30. Rxc5 Bb6 31. Rc2 $11 {
Despite Black's position being a bit easier, White should be ok with correct
play.}) 26... g4 $1 27. Nfd2 {Giri improves his position with strong
centralization now:} ({In case of} 27. Nh2 Bxc4 28. Rxc4 h5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Rh2]
, White's position looks unpleasant.}) 27... Rd8 28. Re1 Rd4 29. Qe3 Qd8 $1 30.
g3 Qd5 31. Na5 Rc8 ({Possibly stronger was} 31... Ra6 $1 {A.Korotylev} 32. Ndc4
(32. Nac4 $2 Rxa2 $19) 32... h5 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rc4] , and the poor position of
both White's knights is a huge problem, for example:} 33. Rc3 Bf5 $19 {[%cal
Rg7h6,Rf5d3]}) 32. Ndc4 {White remains under pressure, but the knights enjoy
more freedom now.} Rb8 (32... Bf8 $5 {[%csl Yc5,Yd6] would be good prophylaxis.
} 33. Qe2 h5 $1 {And White is deprived of the idea seen in the game.}) 33. Qe2
{Anand skillfully prepares a solid regrouping.} Bf8 34. Ne3 $1 Qe4 ({Of course
not} 34... Qxa2 $2 35. Qxa2 Bxa2 36. Nc6 $16 {[%csl Rb8,Rd4]}) 35. Nb3 $1 {
A nice resource, sacrificing a pawn to get rid of Black's bishop pair. Also,
in the resulting position, White manages to activate his forces.} Bxb3 (35...
Rdb4 36. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1e8]}) 36. axb3 Rxb3 (36... Qxe5 37. Qa2 $1 {[%csl Ra7]
[%cal Ge3g4]} Qc7 38. b4 $1 $132 {[%cal Ye3d5] also offers enough counterplay
for White.}) 37. Qa2 Qb7 38. Qc2 (38. e6 $5 fxe6 39. Nc4 $44 {was another
interesting try.}) 38... Rb2 39. Qf5 Qe4 (39... Qf3 $5 40. Qxf3 gxf3 {[%csl
Gf3] was a worthy try, as the f3-pawn might be very annoying for White.}) 40.
Qxe4 Rxe4 41. Ra1 $6 (41. Red1 Rd4 $15 {is still better for Black.}) (41. Nc4 {
seems the best defensive attempt, but after} Rxe1+ 42. Rxe1 Rb4 43. Rc1 h5 44.
Kf1 Bh6 45. Rc2 {, White keeps being pressure, although still fighting hard.})
41... c4 $1 {[%cal Gf8c5] White's position becomes even more difficult after
the activation of the bishop.} 42. Rxa7 Bc5 43. Ra8+ Kh7 44. Rf1 c3 45. Rc8 Bd4
46. Rc7 Rxe5 ({But not} 46... Kg6 $2 47. Rc6+ Kh7 48. Nf5 $1 {, and White
unexpectedly gets counterplay.} Bxe5 (48... c2 49. Rc1) 49. Rxh6+ Kg8 50. Rc6
$11) 47. Rxf7+ $2 {This was meant to be Anand's decisive mistake...} (47. Nxg4
Rf5 48. Rc4 $17 {was White's objectively best try.}) 47... Kg6 48. Rd7 Bxe3 49.
fxe3 Rd2 $2 {... if Giri hadn't missed his chance!} (49... Rb6 $1 {was the
difficult winning move. Black can exploit his strong passed pawn and the
weaknesses in White's camp.} 50. Rc7 ({Also losing is} 50. Rd4 h5 51. e4 Rc5
52. Rdd1 c2 53. Rc1 Rf6 $1 54. Rfe1 Rf3 55. Kg2 Rcc3 $19) 50... Rxe3 51. Rf4 $1
{A.Korotylev} h5 $1 (51... Rxg3+ $2 {is a mistake:} 52. Kf2 Rd3 53. Rxg4+ Kf6
54. Rf4+ Ke5 55. Rfc4 Rb2+ 56. Ke1 {And White achieves the draw, for example:}
Rh3 57. R7c5+ Ke6 58. Rc6+ $11) 52. Kf2 Rd3 53. Rc5 Rb2+ 54. Kg1 Rd1+ 55. Rf1
Rxf1+ 56. Kxf1 c2 57. Ke1 Rb1+ 58. Kd2 Rg1 59. Rxc2 Rxg3 60. Rc6+ Kf5 61. Rc5+
Kf4 62. Rxh5 Ra3 63. Ke2 Ra2+ 64. Kf1 Kg3 $19 {[%cal Gg3h2,Gg4g2]}) (49... Rc5
50. Rd6+ $11 {is just a draw, which shows why Black needs to control the third
rank.}) 50. Rc7 $1 {[%cal Rc7c6,Rc7c3] And Anand had survived.} (50. Rc7 c2 51.
Rc6+ $11 {is a draw.}) 1/2-1/2

