1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 Nd7 ({
Let's see other ways to reach this structure:} 7... g6 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O
10. Re1 {White has many different options to prepare e3-e4 here.} (10. Qe2 {
looks like the most harmless.} Nd7 11. e4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5 13. d5 Nb6 {[%cal
Gc8g4] , and White will have more problems dealing with the pin on g4, as} 14.
h3 $2 {is bad due to the tactical idea} Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Bxh3 $1 $17) (10. Qc2 {
the queen proves to be misplaced on c2 as well.} Nd7 11. e4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5
13. d5 Nb6 14. Bb3 Bg4 15. Nd2 Rac8 16. Qd3 Rfd8 {Black has already mobilized
all his forces.} 17. Nc4 {Smirnov,A (2529)-Illingworth,M (2524)/Gold Coast op
2018 (8)/1-0 A nice continuation now could be} Nxc4 18. Bxc4 Bf8 $1 {[%csl Gf8]
, as Black improves his worst piece.} 19. h3 Bd7 20. Qe3 cxd5 21. Nxd5 Qg5 $1
$11 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gc5d4] , and by transferring the bishop to d4 Black has a
nice position.}) (10. Rc1 {is the move-order that could transpose to the game,
but here it provides an extra option for White:} Nd7 11. e4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5
13. d5 Nb6 14. dxc6 $5 bxc6 (14... Nxc4 $2 15. Nd5 $1 $18) 15. Be2 $1 {This
might seem like a clever way to improve White's chances, as Bg4 is not a
threat anymore. Still, the same Aronian shows us the path to solve any problem
for Black:} h5 $5 {[%cal Gg7h6] Improving the bishop via h6 is a useful idea
to remember.} 16. Qc2 Rd8 17. Na4 Bg4 $1 18. Rfd1 (18. Nxb6 axb6 19. Qxc6 Rxa2
20. Qxf6 Bxf6 21. Rc6 Rxb2 $11) 18... Bh6 $11 {Mamedyarov,S (2752)-Aronian,L  
(2741) /EU-chT (Men) 16th 2007 (8.1)/1/2-1/2, and Black is fine. The following
variation shows how things could develop in case of forced play:} 19. Nxb6
Rxd1+ 20. Bxd1 axb6 21. Qxc6 Qxc6 22. Rxc6 Rxa2 23. Rxg6+ fxg6 24. Bb3+ Kg7 25.
Bxa2 Bxf3 26. gxf3 $11) 10... Nd7 11. e4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5 13. d5 Rd8 $1 {
This subtle idea keeps more options for Black.} (13... Nb6 {is more popular,
but after} 14. Bb3 Bg4 15. Re3 Rad8 16. h3 {[%cal Yd1e2,Ya1d1] White manages
to consolidate his position in the centre, with nice prospects.}) 14. Re3 {
As White is still thinking about Nb6 followed by Bg4, this move makes a lot of
sense. But now comes the surprise:} b5 $1 {Aronian's move radically changes
the character of the game.} 15. dxc6 (15. Bb3 $2 {is a serious mistake now:}
Nb6 16. Rd3 c5 $1 $17 {Martirosyan,H (3090)-Deac,B (2748)/Titled Tuesday
intern op 14th April blitz 2020 (6)/0-1, with a nearly winning advantage for
Black already.}) 15... bxc4 16. Nd5 $6 Qe6 $1 17. cxd7 (17. Nc7 $2 Qxc6 18.
Nxa8 Qxa8 $19) 17... Rxd7 $15 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc8b7] ;Kramnik,V (2801)
-Aronian, L (2820)/Zuerich m 2012 (1)/0-1, and suddenly becomes clear that
White's knight is not stable on d5. Black's position already looks easier and
Aronian demonstrated that with superb technique.}) 8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 g6 10.
O-O Bg7 11. e4 e5 12. d5 Nb6 {The move order chosen by White proved to be good
only for Black, as the trick dxc6 doesn't work with the king on e8.} 13. Bb3 (
13. Be2 {Without playing dxc6 first, this retreat makes little sense.}) 13...
O-O 14. Rc1 Rd8 15. Qe2 (15. h3 {was played by Topalov to avoid the pin on g4.
Still, Aronian was able to find an adequate place for his light-squared bishop:
} Bd7 16. Qe2 Be8 $1 {The bishop might look ugly on e8, but actually it does a
nice job defending both sides and stays out of the way of other pieces.} 17.
Rfd1 Bf8 $1 {Aronian's bishops sit patiently on the back rank, waiting for the
best moment to become active.} 18. dxc6 {Topalov understands that after Rac8
Black would be better prepared for any change in the structure, so he goes for
it right now.} Bxc6 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 $5 Bd6 21. Nd2 Qe7 22. Ne4 Kg7 (22...
f5 $2 23. Nc5 $1 {was White's idea.}) 23. Re1 {Topalov,V (2805)-Aronian, L  
(2781)/Linares 27th 2010 (8)/1/2-1/2} Bb4 $5 {was a safe option for Black now,
when White could try} 24. d6 $5 (24. Red1 Bd6 $11) 24... Bxd6 25. Nxd6 Qxd6 26.
Qxe5+ Qxe5 27. Rxe5 Rd7 $11 {Although White might claim a minimal advantage,
having the bishop against the knight, the position remains balanced.}) 15...
Bg4 (15... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7e8,Gg7f8,Ga8c8] is an option if Black wants to keep
more pieces on the board.}) 16. dxc6 {White needs to release the tension to
create some imbalance.} ({After} 16. Rfd1 cxd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxf3 19.
Qxf3 Qxf3 20. gxf3 Rd7 $11 {Black is totally fine.}) 16... bxc6 {[%csl Gc6]
White hopes to exploit this pawn as a weakness in Black's camp. On the other
hand, the pawn keeps the important d5-square under control, gives the open
b-file to Black and as long as there are many pieces on the board, there is no
risky of lacking defenders for the pawn.} 17. Nd1 $5 {[%cal Gd1e3] White aims
to release the pin with this knight.} (17. Na4 {[%cal Ya4c5] looks more
natural, but Black has a strong continuation now:} Rd4 $1 18. Nc5 a5 $1 19. Rc3
a4 20. Bc2 Qd6 $36 {Simonet Pons,M (2260)-Perez Candelario,M (2511)/Andorra op
25th 2007 (8)/0-1, and Black took over the initiative.}) 17... a5 $1 {A nice
and thematic idea to disturb White's position.} 18. Ne3 h5 $1 {Another
instructive move, keeping the tension and vacating h6 for the Bg7.} 19. h3 ({
White's position looks strange in case of} 19. Nxg4 hxg4 20. Ne1 a4 $1 21. Bc2
Bh6 22. Rd1 Qe6 $15) (19. Rfd1 a4 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Bc2 Bf8 $1 {[%cal Yf8c5]
also seems at least fine for Black.}) 19... Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Qxf3 21. gxf3 a4 22.
Bd1 ({Black keeps a solid position after} 22. Bc2 Bf8 23. Rfd1 Rd4 24. Bd3 c5
$11) 22... Rd2 $1 {At this point it is already White who is looking for
equality.} 23. Rxc6 (23. Rc2 Rxc2 24. Bxc2 Bh6 25. Rd1 Bxe3 26. fxe3 Nc4 $1 {
seems at least ok for Black.}) 23... Rxb2 24. Bc2 Nd7 25. Bd3 $1 Rxa2 26. Bc4 {
White also activates his position now.} Rb2 27. Rc7 Nf8 ({White also regains
the pawn after} 27... Rd2 28. Bd5 Rd8 29. Ra1 $11) 28. Rxf7 Kh8 29. Bd5 Ra6 30.
Ra1 Nh7 31. Bc4 Ra8 32. Bd5 Ra6 33. Bc4 Ra8 34. Bd5 Ra6 {This game and its
notes provide nice examples of Aronian's games in this structure for black
players.} 1/2-1/2

