1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 Nd7 8. Bd3
dxc4 9. Bxc4 g6 10. O-O Bg7 11. Rc1 O-O 12. e4 Rd8 13. e5 Qe7 14. Re1 b5 $1 {
The beginning of a very concrete plan to solve Black's problems.} (14... b6 {
is a more restrained approach, aiming to finish Black's development first and
then look for the breakthrough c6-c5. The problem is that it gives White time
to consolidate his position as well:} 15. Qe2 a6 (15... Bb7 16. Ba6 $1 Bxa6 17.
Qxa6 {[%cal Gc3e4] with Ne4 coming in the next move looks pleasant for White.})
(15... c5 16. d5 $36) 16. Bd3 Bb7 17. Be4 Rab8 18. Na4 $1 {Mamedyarov,S (2752)
-Van Wely,L (2680)/Hoogeveen Essent Crown 11th 2007 (1)/1-0 And Black still
had problems to solve.}) 15. Bd3 Bb7 16. Ne4 {[%csl Gc5,Gd6] White's position
seems much better...} (16. Be4 $2 {is a mistake now due to} Nxe5 $1 $19) 16...
c5 $1 {... and that would be true, if not for this move. Black manages to
solve his problems with a temporary pawn sacrifice.} 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. dxc5 ({
In case of} 18. Rxc5 {, Black has} Rxd4 $1 19. Rxb5 Rb4 20. Rxb4 Qxb4 21. Qb3
a5 $1 {[%cal Gb7h1,Gb4e1,Gg7a1] , when Black has excellent piece play to
compensate for the pawn, for instance:} 22. Bc4 $5 Qxb3 23. axb3 (23. Bxb3 Rc8
{[%cal Yc8c5]}) 23... Rd8 24. Kf1 g5 25. h3 Bxf3 26. gxf3 Rc8 $15 {[%cal Gc8c5]
}) 18... Qc7 19. Re3 $6 {A bit careless.} (19. c6 Bxc6 20. Qc2 {looks strong,
but} Qd7 $1 {keeps everything under control.}) (19. h4 $5 {was played in
another game, and it seems a better try.} b4 $5 {Aiming to avoid b4 by White.}
20. h5 g5 21. Re3 Rac8 22. Qe2 Bxf3 23. Qxf3 Rd5 24. c6 a5 25. Qe4 Kf8 $11 {
[%csl Ye5] ;Khalifman, A (2623)-Bukavshin,I (2647)/RUS-ch Higher League 68th
2015 (5)/0-1 And Black regained the pawn.}) 19... Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Bxe5 {[%csl
Gb2,Gh2] The initiative is already on Black's side.} 21. Rc2 Bxh2+ 22. Kf1 (22.
Kh1 $2 {[%csl Rh1] would be worse, as the king is vulnerable to back rank
threats.}) 22... Be5 (22... Bf4 $1 {was a nice touch to disturb White's pieces.
} 23. Re4 Be5 24. Bxb5 Rab8 25. Qe2 Bd4 {[%cal Gc7h2]} 26. g3 e5 27. c6 Kg7 $15
{[%cal Gf7f5] And White's position remains unpleasant.}) 23. Bxb5 Rab8 24. Qe2
$2 (24. a4 {was a better try.}) 24... Rd5 $2 {This allows a surprising idea.} (
24... Bd4 $1 {would be more precise, when Black develops a strong attack:} 25.
Rf3 (25. Re4 $2 Qh2 $19) 25... Rd5 26. b4 a6 $1 27. Bc4 (27. Bxa6 Rxb4 $19)
27... Rxc5 $1 $19 {A nice resource, and Black wins.}) 25. b4 $2 {White misses
his chance.} (25. Bc6 $3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] was the saving idea.} Qxc6 26. Rxe5
Rd4 27. Kg1 Rbd8 28. Rc1 $13 {And the fight goes on.}) 25... Qd8 $5 ({Black
still had a stronger option:} 25... a5 $1 26. a3 (26. bxa5 Bd4 27. Rb3 Bxc5 28.
g3 Qxa5 $17) 26... Bg7 27. g3 (27. Bc4 Rxc5 $1 $19 {[%cal Gb8b1]}) 27... axb4
28. axb4 Qb7 29. Bc4 Rxc5 $1 $19 {[%cal Rb7h1]}) 26. Ke1 $4 {The decisive
mistake.} (26. g3 {seemed more natural, and it was White's best defensive try.
Still, after} Rd1+ 27. Kg2 Qd5+ 28. Rf3 Qd4 {[%cal Gd4a1] , Black keeps a
promising attack, for example:} 29. Rfc3 $8 (29. Rcc3 $2 Rd2 $19) 29... Qxb4
$15) 26... Qh4 $19 {[%csl Rb4,Rh1] White is unable to defend against the
invasion of Black's pieces.} 27. Re4 (27. a3 Rxb5 $1 28. Qxb5 Qh1+ 29. Qf1 (29.
Ke2 Qd1#) 29... Rd1+ $19) 27... Qh1+ 28. Qf1 Qh5 $1 29. g4 (29. Qe2 Rxb5 $1 $19
) 29... Qg5 {[%csl Re1] White's position is completely ruined by his lack of
coordination and the return of the king to e1.} 30. Qe2 Qh4 31. Bd3 Rbd8 32. g5
(32. Re3 Bf4 33. Rf3 Qh1+ 34. Qf1 Qxf3 $19) 32... Bf4 33. Qf3 Rxd3 34. Rxf4 Qh2
0-1

