{Does the idea c6-c5 work here?} 15... c5 $1 {Yes! Black sacrifices the pawn
on b5 now, but the idea remains the same: To get active piece play.} 16. Nxb5 (
16. dxc5 {White didn't achieve any advantage after} Qxc5 17. Nxb5 Qb6 18. Nbd4
Bb7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 19. Be4 Ba6 20. Bd3 Bb7 $11 {Timofeev,A (2650)-Jakovenko,D 
(2729)/RUS-chT 19th 2012 (6)/1/2-1/2}) (16. d5 $2 {looks like a strong reply,
but after} c4 17. Bb1 Bb7 18. d6 Qd8 {[%csl Re5] White is the side facing
problems in the centre.}) 16... Bb7 {[%csl Yd4,Ye5] And White has no time to
consolidate his centre. For example:} 17. Nxa7 $2 Ra8 18. Nb5 Bxf3 19. Qxf3
cxd4 20. Be4 Nxe5 21. Qb3 Rab8 $19 {Pardo Simon,D (2441)-Potkin,V (2647)/
Barcelona Sants op 15th 2013 (9)/0-1, and Black's central mass proved to be
stronger than White's queenside pawns.} *

