1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 g6 8. Bd3
Bg7 9. e4 O-O 10. O-O Qd8 $5 {An interesting line, preparing to undermine
White's centre.} 11. e5 ({In case of} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. e5 c5 $1 $132 {or}) (
11. Re1 c5 $1 $132 {, Black gets nice counterplay.}) 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 c5 $1
{This is the point. Black doesn't need more time to prepare this advance.} 13.
dxc5 (13. d5 exd5 14. Bxd5 Nc6 $11 {Muradli,M (2352)-Gasimov,P (2375)/
Nakhchivan op 2016 (9)/0-1 is totally harmless for Black.}) 13... Nd7 14. Qe2 {
The most natural, bringing the rooks to the centre immediately.} (14. Qd6 $2 {
looks nice, but it is actually a blunder:} Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxd6 16. cxd6 Bxe5 17.
Rfd1 Rd8 $17 {[%csl Rd6] ;Stinka,J (2299)-Navara,D (2719)/CZE-ch Plzen 2020 (2)
/ 0-1, and White loses the pawn.}) 14... Nxc5 15. Rad1 (15. Rfd1 Qe7 16. Nb5 {
is a different plan, trying to manoeuvre the knight to d6 quickly. This idea
forces Black to look for counterplay against e5:} Bd7 17. Nd6 Bc6 ({Giri once
played} 17... a5 $2 {to secure the position of his Nc5, but after} 18. Qe3 b6
19. Nd4 Rad8 20. Rd2 $16 {Lenic,L (2650)-Giri,A (2762)/EU-chT (Men) 21st 2017 
(9.1)/1-0, White had a pleasant advantage.}) 18. Nd4 Qg5 $1 $132 {[%csl Ge5,
Gg2] ;Lupulescu,C (2618)-Mamedyarov,S (2761)/Olympiad-42 Baku 2016 (4.1)/0-1,
and Black achieved nice counterplay before White was able to consolidate his
advantage.}) 15... Qe7 16. Rd6 {At first sight a very logical and good idea.
White intends to double rooks on the d-file and slowly exploit his space
advantage. However, Giri has a clever idea in mind to neutralize this plan.} b6
({After} 16... Bd7 17. Qe3 Rfc8 18. Rfd1 Be8 19. Bb5 $5 Bxb5 20. Nxb5 {, I
don't believe that Black has solved all his problems, despite the engine's
evaluation of equality.}) 17. Rfd1 Nb7 $1 {First Black kicks back the rook.}
18. R6d2 Na5 $1 {And now the bishop! It's a rare thing that the knight has to
leave the centre and go to the edge - and not the opposite - to improve the
position.} 19. Bd3 ({Black is also fine after} 19. Bb5 Bb7 20. Rd7 Bxf3 21.
Qxf3 Qc5 $1 {[%csl Ye5] Now} 22. Rxf7 $6 Rxf7 23. Qxa8+ Rf8 {[%csl Re5,Rf2]
seems risky for White.}) 19... Bb7 20. Be4 Rad8 {Black has managed to develop
his queenside thanks to the manoeuvre Nb7-a5.} 21. Rd6 (21. Bxb7 Rxd2 $1 ({
But not} 21... Nxb7 $2 22. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c6]} Na5 23. f4 $16 {And White is
better.}) 22. Qxd2 Nxb7 23. Qd7 {Black has two options now:} Re8 ({Or} 23...
Qxd7 $5 24. Rxd7 Nc5 25. Rxa7 Nd3 $1 $132 {[%csl Yb2,Ye5]}) 24. a3 Nc5 25. Qxe7
Rxe7 $11) 21... Bxe4 22. Nxe4 Nb7 $1 {The knight comes in time to control d6
again.} 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 {Giri has succesfully solved his opening problems.} 24.
h4 (24. Rc1 Rd5 $132) 24... Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Nc5 26. Qc2 ({In case of} 26. Nd6 {
, Black plays} Nb7 {, and White can't make progress, as} 27. Qd2 $2 (27. Ne4
$11) 27... Nxd6 $1 28. exd6 Qd7 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yg7f8] looks already
dangerous for him, since the d6-pawn becomes a weakness now.}) 26... Nxe4 27.
Qxe4 Qc7 {The position is probably balanced with correct play by both sides,
but Black's moves seem already a bit easier.} 28. Qd4 (28. Qe2 Qc1+ 29. Kh2 Bf8
30. b3 $11 {was perhaps safer.}) 28... Qc2 {[%cal Gc2b1]} 29. a3 Bf8 $1 {
The bishop is finally back in the game.} 30. Qd2 Qb1+ 31. Kh2 a5 $1 {Giri
secures c5 for the bishop and prepares to fix the queenside pawns as targets
for the bishop in the future.} 32. g4 $2 {A sign of desperation, which only
helps Black.} (32. g3 {was more solid, though after} Kg7 33. Ne1 Qe4 34. Nd3 a4
$15 {, Black's position keeps improving.}) 32... Kg7 33. Kg3 a4 $1 {[%csl Ga3,
Gb2] The queenside pawns are permanent targets for Black now.} 34. Ne1 {
Bacrot tries to bring the knight to help on the queenside, but his position is
already very unpleasant.} Be7 (34... Bc5 {was equally good.} 35. Kf3 (35. Nd3
Qg1+ 36. Kh3 Qh1+ 37. Kg3 Be7 $19) 35... h5 $1 36. gxh5 Qf5+ 37. Qf4 Qxf4+ 38.
Kxf4 Bxf2 39. Nd3 Bxh4 40. hxg6 Kxg6 $19 {With a winning endgame for Black
thanks to the fixed pawn on b2.}) 35. f3 b5 36. f4 $2 Qe4 37. Nf3 Bc5 {[%cal
Rc5e3] White's position is overextended, and it is clear that sooner or later
something will fall.} 38. Qd8 (38. Qe1 Be3 $19) 38... Qe2 39. Qf6+ Kg8 40. Qd8+
Kh7 41. Qa8 Be3 42. Qb7 Kg7 43. f5 Qf2+ {An impressive technical win by Giri.}
(43... Qf2+ 44. Kh3 Bf4 45. f6+ Kg8 46. Qb8+ Kh7 $19) 0-1

