1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 $5 {The Semi-Slav is a very
rich defence, which offers many ideas and possibilities for both sides. This
move characterizes the Moscow Variation.} 6. Bxf6 {The true Moscow Variation.}
({White can keep the bishop pair at the cost of one pawn with} 6. Bh4 dxc4 {
, entering the sharp Anti-Moscow Gambit. This move will be deeply analysed in
the next database.}) 6... Qxf6 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8] After only six moves we can see
that a complex middlegame is ahead. Black has won the bishop pair but has only
made moves with pawns and his queen, which means that White has a visible
advantage in development. Also, White naturally enjoys a bit more space for
the pieces, which could be increased in case of a timely advance e2-e4. Having
said that, I think the Moscow is the right choice for ambitious players for
two reasons: 1) Black has already achieved an unbalanced game after the
exchange and 2) the triangle c6-d5-e6 makes Black's position very solid, in a
way that White can hardly make progress without increasing the tension in the
centre - which could open diagonals for the bishops. Speaking about plans,
while White tries to increase the space and development advantage by means of
preparing the advance e2-e4, Black usually seeks for the right moment of
striking in the centre with either c6-c5 or e6-e5, activating the bishops.} 7.
e3 ({In Chapter 1 we analyse some rare moves for White, such as} 7. e4 $6 {
, opening the centre immediately, but the only way to justify this plan is by
accepting the risks of} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bb4+ $1 9. Ke2 {[%csl Ge2] , when the
weird position of the king on e2 might bring problems for White's development.}
) (7. a3 $5 {, preparing the advance e2-e4 without fearing the check on b4, is
also seen in Chapter 1. This little move is a worthy try and has been played
by a few grandmasters, which means that it is good to know how to face it.}) (
7. Rc1 {is a normal developing move, but simple analysis reveals that it is
not an ideal move order for White, as after} dxc4 $1 {, Black has no problems
equalising. This move and}) (7. cxd5 {are also briefly mentioned in Chapter 1
as slightly inferior move orders, which allow Black to get a good game by
simple means.}) ({In Chapter 2 I check all early queen moves for White. All of
them have the same goal: to prepare the advance e2-e4. Still,} 7. Qb3 {[%cal
Ge2e4] seems to be the most serious. I offer two ways of dealing with this
line: the solid} Nd7 ({and} 7... a5 $5 {, an interesting counterattack on the
flank. Both moves look playable and lead to interesting positions.})) ({
Other queen moves look harmless for Black.} 7. Qc2 {was seen even in top-level
games, but after} dxc4 $1 {the time spent by White to regain the pawn allows
Black to get a good game with nice development.}) (7. Qd2 {is probably the
most harmless. After the same reply} dxc4 $1 {[%csl Yd2] , White's last move
seems pointless.}) ({Finally} 7. Qd3 {seems a sensible alternative to prepare
e2-e4 while keeping c4 protected, but there are some issues here as well:} Nd7
8. e4 dxc4 $1 9. Qxc4 e5 10. d5 {[%csl Gc4] , with a structure that resembles
those seen in Chapter 6, but the exposed position of the queen allows Black to
develop more easily.}) (7. g3 $5 {is a very interesting way to look for
different positions. White aims to exploit the advance e2-e4 in form of
Catalan-type pressure. The critical test of White's idea here is} Nd7 8. Bg2
dxc4 $1 {, leading to complex and double-edged positions, which are analysed
in Chapter 3.}) 7... g6 $5 {Despite some sidelines in which Black develops the
bishop on the f8-a3 diagonal, it is fair to say that it belongs to g7 in the
Moscow. The bishop has many purposes here: It keeps the kingside safe and at
the same time helps Black's plans of breaking in the centre by either c6-c5 or
e6-e5 at the right moment.} 8. Bd3 ({In Chapter 4 we check two ambitious
options for White to avoid common theory: the exotic} 8. e4 $6 {, when White
has spent two moves (e2-e3-e4) to advance the pawn, but on the other hand
Black has weakened the dark squares on the kingside with g7-g6, making things
more complicated, and}) (8. Ne5 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1d2,Ge1c1] , with the
ambitious plan of reinforcing the knight in the centre with f2-f4, followed by
Qd2, 0-0-0 and a pawn storm on the kingside. The ensuing positions tend to be
very tense and double-edged.}) (8. Rc1 {White can go for a fixed structure
after} Nd7 9. Be2 Bg7 10. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gb2b4] , with the famous Carlsbad
Structure on the board, when the well-known minority attack b4-b5 is a natural
idea for White. Still, analysis and recent games of Chapter 5 prove that Black
can deal with this plan.}) ({To finish, in Chapter 8 we see the small but
important differences of} 8. Be2 {compared to the mainline 8.Bd3, although in
many cases it transposes to positions seen in previous chapters.}) 8... Bg7 9.
O-O O-O 10. e4 {This seems the most direct way of exploiting White's lead in
development. We focus on this position in Chapter 7, where my main suggestion
is the less explored} ({All options below are analysed in Chapter 6:} 10. Rc1)
(10. Qe2 {[%emt 0:00:06] Chapter}) (10. Ne5 $5 {[%emt 0:00:06] Chapter}) (10.
Qc2 {[%emt 0:00:06] Chapter}) ({And} 10. Re1 {All these moves aim to improve
White's position by developing more pieces before going for direct action in
the centre. Although it is an understandable strategy, Black has plenty of
useful developing moves as well, and in some cases when White plays too slowly,
it is Black who takes the chance of striking first.}) 10... Qd8 $5 {The queen
has to retreat anyway at some point, and here it supports Black's actions to
undermine the opponent's centre.} ({I also give an alternative plan in the
more flexible} 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nd7 {, when despite having a somewhat
restricted game, analysis shows that Black can solve his opening problems with
dynamic play.}) 11. e5 (11. Re1 c5 $1 {and}) (11. cxd5 exd5 12. e5 c5 $1 $132 {
[%cal Gb8c6] are nice examples of active play for Black.}) {Now we can break
in the centre with} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 c5 $1 {[%csl Yd4,Ye5] , with an
interesting position. White's chances of an advantage rely on trying to
exploit the small lead in development by active play and exerting pressure in
the centre. On the other hand, Black usually keeps a solid position and has
some nice resources to solve his opening problems satisfactorily.} *

