1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e4 $6 {
Let's start with rare lines and slightly inferior move-orders. This one is the
most popular, trying to exploit White's lead in development by immediately
opening the centre. On the other hand, Black is also happy with such
development, as the bishops might become very active.} (7. Rc1 {is very normal,
but it gives Black the chance of exploiting the move-order by means of} dxc4 $5
8. Ne5 $5 $146 ({Black was able to keep the pawn after} 8. a4 Bb4 $17 {[%cal
Gb7b5] ; Urkedal,F (1599)-Zhao,P (2029)/Wch U12 Belfort 2005 (5)/0-1}) (8. e3
b5 {is also good for Black.}) 8... Nd7 {The simplest, giving back the pawn for
quick development.} ({In case of} 8... b5 {, White goes for Catalan-type
positions:} 9. g3 Bb7 10. Bg2 Bb4 11. O-O {[%cal Gc3b5]} Qe7 12. b3 $1 $44 {
, with typical good compensation for the pawn.}) 9. Nxc4 e5 $1 {Black has
already solved his opening problems and has a good position, for example} 10.
d5 Nb6 (10... Bb4 $11 {is also fine.}) 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. g3 Bc5 13. e3 O-O $11)
({I should mention that} 7. cxd5 {is not a bad move, but it is surely a bit
hasty. The main reason for such an evaluation is that Black' position is still
very flexible, and releasing the tension in the centre makes it easier for the
second player to find the best squares for the pieces.} exd5 8. e3 (8. g3 {
also seems harmless. We will see in Chapter 3 that this plan is much more
promising when White keeps the tension in the centre. A recent game went} Qd8
9. Bg2 Be7 10. Qc2 O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. e4 {The only breakthrough that makes
sense.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nf6 14. Nc3 Re8 {Dragun,K (2614)-Lenderman,A (2573)/PRO
League Atlantic rapid 2017 (4)/1/2-1/2 Black's position seems already easier.})
({After} 8. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Nd7 9. e3 Bd6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Qd8 12. Qc2
Re8 {, we have a typical Carlsbad position, but White has no easy way to
develop the usual minority attack (b4-b5) here, and the exchange on f6 makes
Black's development considerably easier. The game goes on, but Black is
totally fine.}) 8... Bd6 $1 {[%csl Gd6] Black could continue with the typical
development g6-Bg7, but since there is no e6-e5 advance anymore, the bishop
looks more useful on d6. Such small details often allow Black to equalise
without problems and to play for more after reaching a good position. The
following game is a nice example in this sense:} 9. Bd3 O-O 10. Qc2 Bg4 11. Nd2
Re8 12. O-O Qh4 13. g3 Qh5 14. Rfe1 Nd7 15. Rab1 Nf8 $36 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ge6g5] ;
Christ,R (2271)-Muse,M (2391)/BL2-Nord 1819 2018 (6.5)/0-1, and the initiative
is already in Black's hands.}) (7. a3 $5 {I never paid attention to this move
until now, but seeing that it was played by many strong players, it became
clear to me that it is not totally harmless.} dxc4 $1 (7... Nd7 8. e4 $1 {
reveals White's goal: to prevent the check on b4, which means that it is
possible to put all the pieces into play in the most active way.}) 8. Ne5 {
Black has at least two equally good paths now:} ({Gambit-like play is hardly a
good plan for White here, as it doesn't pose problems for Black's development:
} 8. e4 b5 9. Be2 a6 10. O-O Nd7 11. a4 Bb7 12. axb5 axb5 13. d5 {Bekker
Jensen,S (2260)-Schlosser, P (2505)/Groningen op 1998 (1)/0-1 Now, after} Rxa1
14. Qxa1 Bc5 $19 {, Black is ready to put the king to safety, with a nearly
winning advantage, as there are no entry points for the queen on the a-file.})
({White can try} 8. g3 Nd7 9. Bg2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne4 Qf5 12. Ned2 {
, but 7.a3 has made no sense in this case. White could have reached an
improved version by playing 7.g3 directly (see Chapter 3). After} e5 $1 13.
Nxc4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Qf6 15. e3 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 $15 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7] ;
Timerkhanov,A (2371) -Goganov,A (2570)/St Petersburg-ch 91st 2018 (2)/0-1, the
bishops provide a pleasant position for Black.}) 8... Nd7 ({The more active} 
8... c5 $5 {is also possible:} 9. Qa4+ Nc6 $5 10. e3 (10. Nxc6 {doesn't win
material in view of} Bd7 11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Qd6 $1 {[%cal Yd7c6] , and Black
is fine.}) 10... cxd4 11. exd4 Be7 12. Nxc6 Bd7 $1 {The same resource works
again nicely.} 13. Bxc4 bxc6 $5 {An interesting decision in order to keep the
two bishops.} 14. O-O O-O 15. Rad1 Rfd8 {Checa,N (2400)-Berczes,D (2479)/Saint
Louis Winter GM 2017 (6)/ 0-1, with a balanced position.}) ({But in case of} 
8... b5 $6 {, White plays} 9. g3 {, after which} Bd6 {now allowed the tactical
idea} 10. Nxb5 $1 {Rapport, R (2534)-Perunovic,M (2558)/ SRB-chT 1st League
2010 (4)/1-0, regaining the pawn.}) 9. Nxc4 Qd8 $1 {Black often brings the
queen back to e7/d8 in the Moscow, where it stays safe from White's pieces.}
10. g3 (10. e3 {Was played once, but Black has no problems after} b5 11. Nd2 b4
$5 {An interesting decision to avoid b2-b4 by White.} 12. axb4 Bxb4 13. Qf3 Bb7
14. Ba6 $5 {Bellon Lopez,J (2425)-Perez Candelario,M (2511)/ESP-chT Honor Gp1
2007 (4)/1/ 2-1/2 Now Black could simply play} Bxa6 15. Rxa6 c5 $11 {, with an
equal game.}) 10... b5 $1 11. Ne3 Bb7 12. Bg2 Qb6 {The queen finds better
prospects on the queenside now.} 13. O-O Be7 14. b4 a5 $1 {White has no time
