1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. Qb3 {In this
chapter we will start by checking early queen moves. Among the logical moves,
this is the most promising, preparing the e2-e4 advance without having to fear
Bb4+, which caused problems for White in Chapter 1.} (7. Qc2 {has the same
goal as Qd3, preparing e2-e4. The drawback is that the c4-pawn is unprotected
now:} dxc4 $1 (7... Nd7 8. e4 {seems an improved version of the line 7.Qd3 Nd7
8.e4, as dxc4 only helps White's development now.}) 8. e3 (8. e4 $2 b5 {
doesn't offer enough compensation for White.}) 8... b5 {I was a bit surprised
when realizing that this position had already occurred in many games between
GMs. Still, practice has proven that Black is fine:} 9. a4 (9. Nxb5 $2 cxb5 10.
Qe4 {[%csl Ra8] seems a nice tactic by White, but it is actually a bad idea.}
Bb4+ $1 11. Kd1 (11. Nd2 O-O 12. Qxa8 e5 $1 $19 {gives a powerful attack for
Black.}) 11... O-O $1 12. Qxa8 Bd7 $19 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gd7c6] You can check
some lines with the computer if you want, but there's no doubt to me that
White's position is desperate: The king is stuck in the centre while Black has
the bishop pair and the idea of e6-e5, opening new lines for the attack. It is
likely that White will be mated before even dreaming about using the extra
exchange.}) 9... Bb7 $1 ({Of course not} 9... Bb4 $2 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Qe4 $18)
10. axb5 ({I found two games by the Greek GM Halkias, which went} 10. Ne5 $5
Bb4 11. axb5 cxb5 {, and now the trick} 12. Bxc4 $5 {Halkias,S (2580)
-Johannesson,I (2338)/ Reykjavik op 23rd 2008 (1)/1-0 Although this line has
worked well for White in both games, I think Black should accept the challenge
of taking the piece:} Bxc3+ $1 13. bxc3 bxc4 14. Qa4+ Kf8 15. Qb5 Qe7 16. Rb1
Bc8 17. Nc6 {This is the most direct way to increase the pressure and create
concrete problems for Black, but it fails because of a subtle reply:} a6 $1 {
[%csl Ga7] After vacating a7 for the queen, Black can play Nxc6 next. And after
} 18. Nxe7 axb5 19. Nxc8 Nd7 20. Nd6 Ke7 $19 {[%cal Gh8b8,Ya8a3] , White's
strategy has completely backfired, as Black is going to exert strong pressure
on the queenside in this endgame.}) 10... cxb5 11. Nxb5 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 ({In case
of} 12. Nd2 {, Black reacts in the same way as we've seen in similar cases:}
O-O $1 13. Nc7 e5 $1 {, when the opening of the centre might bring problems
for White. In practice, Black always gets a strong initiative. This is why my
engine recommends the careful} 14. Bxc4 exd4 15. Nd5 $11 {, with a balanced
position.}) 12... O-O 13. Be2 (13. Ne5 {was a creative attempt, but it doesn't
seem enough for an advantage:} Rc8 14. Bxc4 Nc6 $5 15. Nxc6 {Vallejo Pons,F  
(2716) -Erdos,V (2608)/Bundesliga 1112 2011 (1.2)/1/2-1/2 Black achieved the
draw after defending a long endgame a pawn down. A more interesting
alternative was} Bxc6 16. f3 Qg5 17. Qe2 Bd5 $5 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Rc1 Bxc3+ 20.
Rxc3 Rxc3 21. bxc3 Rc8 $44 {, with nice compensation for the pawn.}) 13... Rc8
(13... Nd7 {is another move-order. The difference is that after} 14. O-O {
, Black has the extra option of} e5 $5 {, which was also enough to equalise in
Alekseev,E (2716)-Gelfand,B (2736)/Moscow Tal Memorial 2nd 2007 (3)/1/2-1/2})
14. O-O Nd7 {It is evident that Black has solved the opening problems quite
well at this point. I even think that White already has to be careful, as the
pressure on the queenside can become a bit unpleasant in some positions.} 15.
Rfc1 ({A clash of generations went} 15. Nd2 Nb6 16. Bf3 {White immediately
gets rid of Black's bishop pair.} Qe7 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. e4 a5 19. Nf3 Nd7 $1 {
The knight goes back to f6 to press White's centre now.} 20. Rfd1 Nf6 21. Nd2
Rab8 {Kortschnoj,V (2602)-Caruana,F (2630)/Amsterdam NH Hotels 3rd 2008 (7)/
0-1, and Black had a comfortable position.}) 15... a5 16. Na4 {[%csl Gc4]
White prepares to grab the c4-pawn.} (16. Qd1 {has a similar idea, but it
allows the active response} e5 $1 {, which lead to an interesting position
