1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 g6 8. Rc1 {
In this chapter I've decided to analyse different moments where White plays
cxd5, reaching the famous Carlsbad structure. This is always an interesting
practical decision, as White avoids a theoretical discussion and gets a solid
position with a definite plan - the famous minority attack. There's no reason
for Black to be afraid of this plan, but it is important to know how to deal
with it, of course.} (8. Qc2 {is another way to "prepare" the exchange,
threatening the same trick as in the mainline.} Nd7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 Bg7
11. O-O (11. b4 Qd6 12. Rb1 O-O 13. O-O {transposes.}) (11. h4 $5 {Apart from
the minority attack, this seems the only alternative that can justify White's
play. Still, I think Black is fine either preventing or allowing White's plan
on the kingside, as he got a playable position in two different games:} Qe7 $5
(11... O-O 12. h5 g5 13. Ne2 Qe7 14. Ng3 Nf6 15. Bf5 $2 Ne4 $1 16. Bxe4 dxe4
17. Nxe4 Bf5 18. Nfd2 Rae8 19. f3 Bh7 20. g4 f5 $1 {Sasikiran,K (2690)
-Karjakin,S (2686)/Foros Aerosvit 2007 (9)/1/2-1/2, and Black's initiative is
already crushing, although White actually survived somehow.}) 12. O-O-O Nf6 13.
Ne5 Ng4 $1 14. Nxg4 Bxg4 15. Rde1 O-O-O 16. h5 g5 17. Kb1 Kb8 $11 {Roiz,M  
(2616)-Rodshtein,M (2530)/ISR-chT Israel 2007 (9.1)/0-1, and Black is ok again.
}) 11... O-O 12. b4 Qd6 {The fact that the Nc3 is protected by the queen
instead of the rook gives Black more tactical ideas.} 13. Rab1 (13. Qb3 {
has only wasted one move (Qc2-b3).} Nb6 14. a4 ({An important point of this
line is to be ready to answer} 14. b5 {with} c5 $1 {, an advance that usually
gives nice active play to compensate for the isolani. White can try} 15. Qa3 $5
{, but the pin is less dangerous than it looks at first sight:} Bg4 $1 16. dxc5
Qe7 $13 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gg4f3] In the end it is Black who exploits the same pin.})
14... Be6 15. Nd2 Nd7 $1 {Black has managed to develop his light-squared
bishop and make the b4-b5 idea less attractive for White.} 16. a5 {Change of
plans.} (16. Rab1 {was an attempt of keeping the possibilities on the
queenside open, but then Black unexpectedly took over with} a5 $5 17. bxa5 Rxa5
{This was possible because the b7-pawn was tactically defended, of course.} 18.
Qc2 b6 19. Nb3 Raa8 20. Qd2 c5 $5 $36 {Sokolov,I (2637)-Dreev,A (2680)/
Hastings 00 75th 2000 (6)/0-1 Black is the side playing with the initiative on
the queenside now, but curiously the winning blow came on the other side of
the board.}) 16... Rfe8 17. Rfc1 a6 18. Na4 Rad8 19. Qc3 Nf8 20. Bc2 Re7 $11 {
[%cal Ye6c8,Gd8e8] ;Bacrot,E (2695)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2683)/Mainz Classic rap
Prelim rapid 2007 (5)/0-1, and Black's position is solid. After retreating the
bishop to c8 to protect b7, a possible plan is to double rooks on the e-file
and look for active play on the kingside with f5-g5-f4, etc.}) ({Again, it is
