17... O-O 18. Nc5 Nxc5 19. Rxc5 Bd7 20. Rfc1 Ra7 21. Ne1 Rfa8 $11 {Yu,Y (2750)
-Giri,A (2769)/Shenzhen Du Te Cup 2017 (4)/1/2-1/2 Black is fine. For me, the
most important thing in these positions for Black is to understand which
pieces should be kept on the board. Although both bishops look passive here,
they do an important defensive job defending the c6-pawn and avoiding Ne5,
which would increase the pressure on the queenside. Keeping queens on the
board is also a good deal for Black, as the Qd6 controls many important
squares in the centre, defends c6 as well and can be combined with the action
of the double rooks on the a-file to generate some counterplay. Above all, it
is not easy to find an effective plan to increase the pressure on c6 for White.
The only logical idea is to transfer the knight to b4, but Black has enough
resources to neutralize it, to exchange one pair of rooks or to just play Bf8.
It is not surprising that Black had no problems and the game was drawn.} *

