1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 g6 8. Bd3
Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Rc1 {In this chapter I would like to analyse some
alternatives to the critical 10.e4. Some of them aim to wait for an early
definition of Black's plans while others just try to keep flexibility and more
ideas available for White.} (10. Re1 {is a useful move to wait for some
definition by Black.} Nd7 11. e4 {[%csl Yd7] At first sight, it seems
pointless to delay e3-e4 since White could have played it one move earlier,
but there is something important to learn about flexibility in these positions.
See the next chapter and White's idea suddenly becomes evident: Developing the
knight to d7, Black has lost the option of my main recommendation in the
mainline 10.e4.} dxc4 12. Bxc4 ({After} 12. e5 Qe7 13. Bxc4 b5 $1 14. Bd3 Rd8 {
we have transposed to the notes of 10...dxc4 in the next chapter.}) 12... e5 $1
{I like this move, fighting for the centre and changing the structure. At
first sight, Black closes the Bg7 and gives White a strong passed pawn in the
centre. As we will see, Black has adequate ways to deal with both issues.} ({
In some games Black has opted for a more flexible approach with} 12... Qe7 {
[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] , planning for slow but solid development, when} 13. e5 {
transposes to the notes of 10...dxc4 from the next chapter again.}) 13. d5 Rd8
$1 {This is a nice way to keep Black's options open.} (13... Nb6 {is more
popular, but after} 14. Bb3 Bg4 15. Re3 Rad8 16. h3 {White manages to
stabilize the position and can fight for a small advantage.}) 14. Re3 {
Considering that Nb6 and Bg4 are still part of Black's plans, this rook lift
makes sense.} (14. h3 {also seems like useful prophylaxis, but Black can react
in the same way as in the mainline:} b5 $1 15. dxc6 (15. Bb3 Nc5 {[%csl Gb3,
Rd5][%cal Gb5b4] looks dangerous for White and} 16. a3 {allows the tactical
trick} Bxh3 $5 17. gxh3 Nxb3 18. Qxb3 Qxf3 19. Re3 Qf6 20. dxc6 Rd2 $1 21. Rf1
Qxc6 $13 {, with an easier game for Black.}) 15... bxc4 {Guthrie,D (2167)-Tan,
J (2239)/London Classic op 4th 2012 (8)/0-1 In the game, White followed in the
steps of our source game Kramnik-Aronian and got similar problems. Instead, he
should have played the safer} 16. cxd7 Rxd7 17. Qe2 Qa6 18. Rad1 Rxd1 19. Rxd1
Be6 $13 {, with chances for both sides.}) (14. Rc1 {was played by Karjakin. I
like the way Motylev developed his play now:} h5 $5 15. h3 Bh6 16. Rc2 Nb6 17.
Bb3 a5 18. a3 Kg7 19. Qe2 Bd7 20. Rd1 Be8 $11 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7e8] ;Karjakin,S 
(2753) -Motylev,A (2658)/RUS-ch 68th Chita 2015 (5)/1/2-1/2, and Black had a
solid position. The manoeuvre Bd7-e8 is very common in this structure, as the
bishop doesn't block the communication between the rooks, keeps important
points (c6,f7) protected and waits patiently to take a more active role in the
