1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 ({Don't mess up the move
order!} 5... dxc4 6. e4 {is the Botvinnik System, when} h6 {doesn't transpose:}
7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Bxc4 $14 {, and White has a pleasant version of the Moscow.})
6. Bh4 dxc4 7. a4 $6 {Although this move can be considered a playable option
against the Botvinnik System, it is at least dubious against the Moscow. The
inclusion of h6/Bh4 makes things favourable for Black.} (7. e3 b5 8. a4 Bb4 {
is the same.}) 7... Bb4 $1 {Of course, the best way to contest White's last
move is to try to keep the extra pawn.} 8. e3 ({In one game White tried} 8.
Bxf6 $5 Qxf6 9. e4 (9. e3 {transposes to 9.Bxf6}) 9... b5 10. e5 Qe7 11. g3 {
White hopes to get Catalan-type compensation for the pawn.} Bb7 12. Bg2 {
Charochkina,D (2317)-Lei,T (2528)/Wch Blitz (Women) blitz 2017 (2)/1/2-1/2
Since White has no immediate threats and the exchange on f6 makes Black's
development easier, she would have a nice position by simply developing the
queenside now:} Nd7 13. O-O a6 14. Nd2 O-O $1 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Rxa8 $1 {
, and Black is clearly better, as} 17. Nxb5 $2 {has a tactical problem:} cxb5
18. Bxb7 Rd8 19. Nf3 Nxe5 $1 $19 {[%cal Re7b7]}) (8. e4 $2 g5 9. Bg3 Nxe4 $17 {
is the obvious advantage for Black of including h6/Bh4.}) (8. Qc2 {prepares
the advance, but in case of} Nbd7 9. e4 b5 $17 {, Black is simply better, as}
10. e5 $2 {finds the direct refutation} g5 11. Nxg5 Nd5 $1 12. Nf3 (12. Nxf7
Qxh4 13. Nxh8 Qxd4 $19 {, and Black is grabbing more material.}) 12... Qa5 13.
Rc1 Qxa4 14. Qxa4 bxa4 $19 {[%cal Ra4a3] , and White's position seems
desperate.}) 8... b5 9. Be2 ({Perhaps a more principled idea is} 9. Nd2 $5 Bb7
10. axb5 ({Black has time to consolidate the queenside in case of} 10. Be2 a6
11. O-O Nbd7 12. Qc2 O-O $17) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 cxb5 12. Qb1 $5 {[%csl Gb5]
[%cal Yd2c4] A typical manoeuvre in such positions, threatening both Qxb5+ and
Nxc4.} (12. Rb1 {is worse, despite having the same idea:} Bc6 13. e4 a6 14. e5
g5 15. Bg3 Ne4 $1 {This is the difference: the queen on b1 would avoid this
useful exchange for Black.} 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Ra1 {Kristiansen,J (2441)
-Nielsen,P (2625)/DEN-ch Silkeborg 2008 (9)/1/2-1/2 , and now the simple
continuation} Nc6 18. f3 Bd5 19. Be2 a5 20. O-O b4 $19 {seems almost winning
for Black.}) 12... Bc6 {The most logical way to avoid both threats.} ({After} 
12... Qb6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ra2 $5 {[%cal Ga2b2] ;Gareyev,T (2525)-Novikov,I 
(2588)/Olympiad-36 Mallorca 2004 (5)/1/2-1/2, the position remains complex.})
13. e4 {Another point of Qb1 is that it supports the advance of White's centre.
} Nbd7 14. Be2 ({White can also try} 14. e5 g5 15. Bg3 Nd5 16. Ne4 {, but the
check on d6 shouldn't scare Black:} a5 $1 17. h4 {The main problem for Black
in these positions is that it is often difficult to find a safe square for the
king, but here things can be solved with the unexpected} (17. Nd6+ $2 Ke7 18.
Nxb5 $2 {is even worse:} Rb8 19. Bxc4 Bxb5 20. Bxb5 Nxc3 $19) 17... Ke7 $1 18.
Qc1 N7b6 $1 19. hxg5 hxg5 20. Qxg5+ Kd7 {, when the king is safe on d7 and
White isn't able to avoid the queen's exchange due to the rook hanging on h1.}
21. Rxh8 Qxg5 22. Nxg5 Rxh8 23. Rxa5 Nxc3 $19 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4] And the two
passed pawns provide a winning advantage for Black.}) 14... Qb6 15. O-O O-O 16.
Bf3 {Sammour Hasbun,J (2463) -Kuljasevic,D (2501)/USA tt ICC INT 2008 (3)/1/
2-1/2 A possible continuation now could be} Rfc8 17. Re1 Bb7 $17 {, and Black
is a healthy pawn up.}) (9. axb5 cxb5 10. Nd2 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bb7 {transposes to
the previous note.}) ({Another plan to put some pressure on Black's queenside
is} 9. Bxf6 $5 Qxf6 10. Ne5 ({If} 10. Be2 Nd7 $1 {prevents White's plan.} 11.
O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O $17) 10... Bb7 11. Be2 O-O 12. Bf3 {White aims to keep
pressure on b5 and c6 to make Black's development harder.} Qe7 13. O-O a6 $5 {
Inviting White to regain the pawn.} ({Black can also try to keep his material
advantage with} 13... Bxc3 $5 14. bxc3 a6 $15 {, but he still has some
development issues to solve.}) 14. axb5 cxb5 15. Nxb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Bxa8 17.
Bxa8 Nd7 18. Nc6 (18. Nxd7 $2 Rxa8 19. Ne5 Bd6 20. Nf3 Ra2 $17 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4]
[%cal Ye7a7] looks much better for Black.}) 18... Qd6 19. Bb7 Qc7 20. Nxb4 Qxb7
$15 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4][%cal Yf8a8,Yd7f6,Yf6d5] White has regained the pawn, but
the queenside majority seems to offer better chances for Black in the
resulting position.}) 9... Nbd7 $1 10. O-O Qb6 $1 {The last two moves were
very precise. Black needs the queen to keep the queenside safe, therefore it
was important to reduce the strength of the pin on f6 by reinforcing the
knight.} 11. Qc2 O-O {Although castling seems pretty natural, it is again the
most precise.} ({This position was reached by transposition in a recent
