pin is} 20. Nxg7 Kxg7 21. Qd2 {, but Black has some nice resources here as
well:} Qb1+ $1 22. Bd1 {Here,} ({If} 22. Ne1 {, the queen goes back.} Qf5 23.
g4 Qf4 24. Qd1 {The pressure on the d-file seems overwhelming, but Black has a
clever way to deal with it:} Rhe8 $3 25. Rxd7 (25. Bf3 Bxf3 26. Nxf3 {is also
met with a beautiful idea:} Qxd6 $3 27. Qxd6 Nf6 $19 {[%cal Gd8d1] And Black
wins.}) 25... Rxe2 $1 $19 {Against either capture on e2, Black regains the
rook, with a winning position.}) 22... Nf6 $3 {is another incredible resource
for Black.} ({The more human} 22... Bc8 $5 {is also possible.}) 23. Rxd8 Rxd8
24. Qxd8 Bd5 $1 {A funny position: White is a rook up, but there is no way to
make use of this huge material advantage.} 25. Ke1 Qe4+ (25... Qxb2 $5) 26. Kd2
Qb1 $1 {[%cal Gb1b2,Gf6e4] Despite the reduced army, Black keeps creating
annoying threats.} 27. Ke1 ({The result is also a draw after} 27. Qe7 c3+ $1
28. bxc3 Ne4+ 29. Ke1 Bb3 30. Qe5+ Kg8 31. Qe8+ Kg7 32. Qe5+ $11) 27... Qe4+
$11) 20... Qb3 $1 {The Nd7 is lost, but Black can at least exchange queens to
secure the king.} (20... Qa4 $2 {is the wrong square for the queen due to} 21.
Qe1 $18 {[%cal Ge2d1]}) 21. Rxd7 (21. Qe1 $2 {doesn't work now in view of} Qxb2
22. Bxc4 Bf6 $1 $17 {With the queen on a4, White would win with Rxf6 now, but
as this idea is prevented here, Black is more than fine.}) ({Another way of
reaching the ending is} 21. Qxb3 cxb3 22. Bxb5 Bxb2 $1 {, when White has won
one pawn back, but the two remaining pawns on Black's queenside provide enough
counterplay. The following lines are not forced but show some possible
developments:} 23. Ke2 $5 ({In case of the direct} 23. Rxd7 Rxd7 24. Bxd7 Bc1
$1 25. N5d4 b2 26. Bf5 a5 $17 {[%csl Ga5,Gb2] , the pawns look very strong.})
23... Bc8 24. Rhd1 Ba3 25. R6d3 g4 $1 {Disturbing White's coordination.} 26.
N3h4 (26. Ne5 $2 Re8 $1 $19) 26... Be7 27. Nxe7 (27. Bxd7 $2 Ba6 $1 {And it is
White who has to deal with an unpleasant pin now.} 28. Ba4 b2 29. Bc2 Bf6 30.
Kd2 Bxd3 31. Bxd3 Rg8 $1 $17 {[%cal Gg8g5]}) 27... Kxe7 28. Re3+ Kf8 29. Rxb3
Kg7 $1 30. Nf5+ ({If} 30. Rbd3 {Black is able to escape the pin with} Rde8+ 31.
Kf1 Ne5 $1) 30... Kf6 31. Nd6 Nb6 32. Rbd3 Be6 33. Ne4+ Ke7 $11) 21... Qxd1+
22. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 23. Bxd1 Bxb2 {[%csl Ga7,Yb2,Gb5,Yb7,Gc4] The endgame is very
sharp and double-edged, of course, and all three results are possible. I like
Black's chances, as three passed pawns supported by the bishop pair can become
very dangerous. On the other hand, White has one more piece and can try to
organize his forces to block and take those pawns. The following lines are not
forced but show some useful ideas for both sides.} 24. Bc2 (24. Ke2 Be4 $1 {
White's position remains a bit cramped.} 25. N3d4 (25. N5d4 $4 g4 $19 {[%csl
Rd4,Rf3]}) 25... a6 26. f3 Bd3+ 27. Kd2 b4 28. Bc2 Bxf5 29. Nxf5 b3 30. Bxb3 $1
cxb3 31. Rb1 Bg7 32. Rxb3 Kg8 $11) 24... a5 25. Ke2 Bc8 $1 {[%csl Gf5] As this
knight cramps Black's position on the kingside, exchanging it seems very
logical.} 26. Nd6 (26. Rd1 Bxf5 27. Bxf5 a4 $13 {The pawns keep approaching
towards promotion.}) 26... Kg7 $1 ({But not} 26... Bd7 $2 27. Rb1 c3 28. Ne5
$16 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ye5d3,Ye5d7]}) 27. Nxg5 $5 (27. Nxb5 {regains one pawn,
but Black can activate the rook now:} Re8+ 28. Kd2 Rd8+ 29. Ke2 Re8+ 30. Kf1
Rd8 $1 $44 {[%csl Gh1][%cal Yd8d5] And White still faces problems to develop
the rook.}) 27... hxg5 28. Rxh8 Kxh8 29. Nxc8 {As usual in times of modern
engines, the fight between the piece and the passed pawns ends in a draw:} a4
30. Nd6 a3 31. Bb1 b4 32. Nxc4 b3 33. Nxa3 (33. Nxb2 $4 a2 $1 $19) 33... Bxa3
$11 *

